Searching for Happiness

Haoyu Fang

Jasmine Then

Theodore Tourneux

Naval Ravikant, a highly successful entrepreneur once tweeted,

The ideal school would teach health, wealth, and happiness. It‘d be free, self-paced, and available to all. It‘d show opposing ideas and students would self-verify truth. No grades, no tests, no diplomas - just learning. Actually, you’re already here. Careful who you follow.

Our team thought that the world happiness data would be one of the best ways to look at these three components in life. The world happiness data set examines over 150 countries(though the exact number depends on the year) and gives surveys to determine how the different elements in our lives, impact our happiness. The data set also includes a happiness score which is the sum of the happiness values across all categories.

Our goal as a team was to find out which area would be the best to live in if you were trying to maximize your happiness. After some initial work with the data we decided that it would be most helpful to not just look at one year, but to examine the data from 2016 to 2019 to make sure that the best country to live in would stay that way! To start off, we will look at how economic factors and happiness are related to each other as it will contextualize our original data set with other published data. We will then examine factors such as government type, how trustful that government is, and how healthy the population is.

Although our initial data set had values for the happiness derived from economic conditions, we decided to see whether people who felt happiest about their financial situation were actually the people earning the most. Thanks to this dot plot and best-fit line, we can clearly see that between 0 and 15000 USD, a small boost in GDP per capita can make a huge deal for happiness and after about $60,000 per year the slope becomes much flatter, though still increasing.

We can also see that throughout the countries for which we have data, GDP and happiness are strongly correlated, though there is more variation between countries, as we look at higher GDP per capita numbers. Our data supports the idea that making and having more money, even at the national scale, is correlated with having more happiness. In hindsight, this seems logical.

Of course, one consideration when deciding where to live is the potential for earnings and wealth accumulation. It logically follows that a country with a GDP per capita of at least $30,000/year would offers greater chances for obtaining happiness.

We also found that the general shape of the graph was relatively constant over the years measured. We know that it is hard to increase GDP more than a few percentage points per year so we can say that one would get the most happiness from living in a country where the GDP was the highest. Nevertheless, we will be sure to check other factors as money is not the only thing that makes people happy!

These dot plots show us that it would be hard to predict how a country’s GDP will change based on the happiness data, however, what we can see is that GDP per capita does not change drastically in a matter of years, as predicted. Therefore, the previous findings will be the only economic based criteria when picking a place to live; after 30K it would be wiser to make one’s choice of country based on the following factors. Since we want to maximize happiness we will continue to look at these 10 countries.

We see above that 2018 seems to have a peak in GDP per capita and thus we were curious as to whether we could see a similar trend in other facets of the happiness data. Indeed, we can see that from 2018 to 2019 the happiness derived from life expectancy increases dramatically.

In order to answer this question, we built a linear graph above called “Happiness Weighted by Life Expectancy Among the ten Happiest Countries”. This graph plots life expectancy weighted happiness on a time series graph. We can clearly see that among these ten countries, the life expectancy impact on happiness increased for all countries from 2018 to 2019. Looking at United Arab Emirates from 2017 to 2018, the people in the United Arab Emirates actually believed their health was less essential that contributes to the calculation of the Happiness than before. The extent to which life expectancy contributed to the calculation of the “Happiness” fell from around 0.73 to 0.67. We can actually attribute this to the Yemen Airstrikes that happened in the United Arab Emirates according to the 2018 world happiness report. Nevertheless, the United Arab Emirates followed the increasing trend of life expectancy. Although life expectancy and economic prosperity are major factors on a country’s aggregate happiness, they are not the only factors we should look at.

Based on our conclusions about these ten nations, we can use data analysis to see if there’s any relation between their “Happiness Scores” and their type of government. For the graph shown above, a new data table was created with columns of country names and their corresponding government type. This new data table was then joined with our World Happiness data set and mutated to sum up “Trust in Government/Corruption” and “Happiness Score” values for each nation across all five years.

My initial hypothesis was that the these countries are run by a democratic type of government. The world has seen what Democracy can do, such as give people freedom, connect nations with one another, and foster cooperation, instead of putting all the power under one person. With this amount of freedom, it could play a major role in determining a nation’s “Happiness Score”.

Based on the plot, these nations seem to be ruled by a Monarchy/Parliamentary form of government. In other words, our initial guess was incorrect. Although a Democracy appears within these ten countries, Monarchies or Parliamentary forms of government come out on top each time. One conclusion that can definitely be made is that Communist states and nations with Military Dictatorship do not rank in the top ten. An interesting point to make is that although Switzerland is a Confederation/Direct Democracy and the United States is a Democracy, they are still able to place in the top ten. We see that Monarchies and Parliamentary forms of government are the most common among people who are happy with how much money they make.

In terms of their Trust in Government and Perception of Corruption, these ten nations seem to have varying levels of happiness, nevertheless, there is a correlation between “Happiness Score” and the amount of trust a nation has in its leadership systems. Higher “Trust in Government” leads to a higher “Happiness Score”. Therefore, one would want to live in a Monarchy/Parliamentary state with a trustful government.

As a result, although our ten countries share similar government types, how much they trust their own government is a different matter. The “Trust in Government” and “Perception of Corruption” variable plays a minor role in determining overall happiness. There are other factors, however, that contribute to the “Happiness Score” which people in this data set found to be more meaningful.

In the end, we found that money can buy you happiness, nonetheless, there are many other factors that should be examined if you want to live a happy life. As we have seen in this analysis, GDP is an important factor in determining happiness. As GDP rises, so does a nation’s “Happiness Score”. Moreover, we have discovered that the happiest countries follow a Monarchy/Parliamentary type of rule. Thus, choosing a nation in Western Europe might be the best choice. Furthermore, we have concluded that the health and life expectancies of a country increase significantly when that nation is happy. All in all, Switzerland and Ireland are countries in which there is a high chance to live happily, due to earnings, as well as a trustworthy government, and a healthy lifestyle. .
